ns1:Book00332c1a-7085-4e00-afe9-612213259995 a ns1:Book ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52984" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Annick ;
    ns1:reviewBody "Chantal Rondeau discusses ancestral foods: “It’s my connection to the land. I have an apartment-size freezer full of moose meat and caribou meat.” Rap duo Mob Bounce explain their transition from influences of gangster rap to traditional drum: “We woke up … old patterns no longer served us … it wasn’t what was going on in the world but what was going on within.”\r Thirty voices are featured in this collection, including academics, students, activists and artists, in chapters such as “Shattering Stereotypes” and “Native Renaissance.” Contributors identify their heritage, demonstrating that a wide range of cultures exist under the generic ‘Native.’ “City Quotes”—on living in specific cities—points out that New York City is on land used by the Lenape; Halifax is on Mi’kmaq traditional territory.\r Artwork, photography and candid portraits of contributors draw readers to the text. A graphic-style illustration depicts Roanna Shebala, contributor of the spoken word piece, “Love You Some Indians.” Across the image, red paint slashes affect—but don’t eclipse—the figure. In another spread, Nicholas Galanin’s artwork is featured: a seated wolf morphs into a wolf-skin spread on the floor: “They see my work … as belonging in a natural history museum with dinosaur bones.”\r Cool and current, uplifting and inspiring, this book includes messages from the editors, as well as writers Joseph Boyden and Wab Kinew." ;
    ns1:name "Urban Tribes: Native Americans in the City" ;
    pbs:isCoupDeCoeur false ;
